{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048172,"nonce":"evyewyCXt+xjY3zlEgjEH+cpYvg=","title":"Consider named axes via Haliax for neural network components","message":"[Imported from GitHub #40] (created 2026-01-26T17:20:18Z)\n\n## Context\n\nFeedbax currently uses jaxtyping for shape/dtype annotations, with disciplined naming conventions for dimensions. This works but can become error-prone as neural network architectures grow in complexity—particularly with attention mechanisms, multi-head structures, or batch/sequence/feature interactions.\n\nNamed tensor libraries address this by making axis semantics explicit in the type system rather than relying on positional indices.\n\n## Named Axis Options\n\n### Haliax (recommended if adopting named axes)\n\n[Haliax](https://github.com/stanford-crfm/haliax) uses explicit `Axis` objects that carry both name and size:\n\n```python\nHead = hax.Axis(\"head\", 8)\nKey = hax.Axis(\"key\", 64)\nPos = hax.Axis(\"position\", 1024)\n\n# Self-documenting operations\nscores = hax.dot(query, key, axis=Key) / jnp.sqrt(Key.size)\n```\n\n**Strengths**:\n- Axis objects carry size, enabling static validation\n- Full FSDP and tensor parallelism support (proven to 70B parameters on TPU v4-2048)\n- Works alongside Equinox modules\n- Powers Stanford's Levanter/Marin for large-scale training\n\n**Trade-offs**:\n- Another abstraction layer over JAX arrays\n- Requires axis-aware API calls (`hax.dot` instead of `jnp.dot`)\n- Most valuable at scale; may be overkill for smaller models\n\n### Penzai named axes (`pz.nx`)\n\nPenzai offers a lighter-weight alternative using string names and `nmap` to lift functions:\n\n```python\n# Tag axes with names\nnamed_arr = arr.tag(\"batch\", \"features\")\n\n# Lift any JAX function to vectorize over named axes\nresult = pz.nx.nmap(jnp.sum)(named_arr.untag(\"features\"))\n```\n\n**Strengths**:\n- Minimal API surface; works with existing JAX functions\n- No redundant size storage (sizes live in the array, names are metadata)\n- Easy to adopt incrementally\n\n**Trade-offs**:\n- Less explicit than Haliax (no static size in axis definition)\n- Limited sharding/parallelism support\n- Designed for interpretability workflows, not training at scale\n\n## When Named Axes Help\n\n1. **Complex broadcasting** - When positional semantics become ambiguous\n2. **Attention mechanisms** - Query/key/value dimension tracking\n3. **Multi-head structures** - Head dimension vs. feature dimension\n4. **Sharding declarations** - Named axes map naturally to mesh axes\n5. **Code reviews** - Self-documenting tensor operations\n\n## When Named Axes Are Overkill\n\n1. **Simple MLPs** - Dimension semantics are obvious\n2. **Physics/mechanics code** - Physical quantities (angles, forces) are already semantic\n3. **Tight dependency budget** - Another library to maintain\n4. **Not hitting dimension bugs** - If current conventions work, don't fix what isn't broken\n\n## Fit with Feedbax\n\nNamed axes would primarily benefit `SimpleStagedNetwork` and similar neural network components. The mechanics/physics code (`AbstractPlant`, `AbstractSkeleton`, `AbstractMuscle`) already has explicit physical semantics—joint angles, muscle lengths, forces—that don't benefit from named axes.\n\n**Hybrid approach**: Use Haliax for NN internals while keeping standard JAX arrays for physics. This is viable since Haliax arrays can be converted to/from standard arrays at component boundaries.\n\n## Recommendation\n\n**Wait unless hitting dimension pain.** Current jaxtyping + naming conventions are adequate for Feedbax's scale. Revisit if:\n- Attention mechanisms or transformers are added\n- Dimension-related bugs become frequent\n- Distributed training across multiple devices is needed\n\nIf adopting, **prefer Haliax** over Penzai's `pz.nx` due to:\n- Explicit axis sizing\n- Better sharding support\n- Active development via Levanter/Marin ecosystem\n\n## References\n\n- [Haliax Documentation](https://haliax.readthedocs.io/en/latest/)\n- [Haliax GitHub](https://github.com/stanford-crfm/haliax)\n- [Levanter (uses Haliax + Equinox)](https://github.com/marin-community/levanter)\n- [Penzai named axes](https://penzai.readthedocs.io/en/stable/notebooks/named_axes.html)\n- [\"Tensor Considered Harmful\" (Alexander Rush)](https://nlp.seas.harvard.edu/NamedTensor)\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}